When it comes to Btrfs, the fear of it eating up your storage is actually a common myth. For a 2TB NVMe filled with modern games, Btrfs will actually save you space compared to Ext4, rather than wasting it.
Here is why Btrfs is an elite choice for your gaming drive and how it manages space:


## 1. Transparent Compression (The Space Saver) 🗜️
Btrfs has a feature called transparent compression (usually zstd).

* When Steam downloads a game, Btrfs compresses the data on the fly before writing it to the NVMe.
* When the game loads, your Ryzen 9800X3D decompresses it instantly. Because the CPU is lightning fast, reading a smaller compressed file off the drive can actually make games load faster than reading uncompressed data.
* Result: A 100GB game might only take up 85GB of physical space on your drive.


## 2. Copy-on-Write Snapshots (Zero Space Backups) 📸
Btrfs snapshots are the ultimate safety net for NixOS, and they use 0 bytes of extra space when you create them.

* If you take a snapshot of your system, Btrfs doesn't copy any files. It just points to the existing data.
* Space is only consumed when files are changed or deleted.
* Gaming Tip: You can easily configure your snapshot tool (like Timeshift or Snapper) to exclude your Steam library folder (~/.local/share/Steam). This way, your system files are safely backed up, but massive game updates won't bloat your snapshots.


## 3. No Rigid Partitioning (Dynamic Subvolumes) 💾
Unlike traditional filesystems where you have to lock in a specific size for your home folder and system root, Btrfs uses "Subvolumes."

* Subvolumes act like folders but behave like partitions.
* They share the exact same pool of 2TB of space dynamically. If your game library grows to 1.5TB, your system root automatically shrinks out of the way to make room.

